

Toxic Dependencies 

[Very little modern software is written from scratch. To avoid re-inventing the wheel, developers depend on libraries, frameworks and tools written by others.](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/dependency-management) 

Toxic Dependencies 

[Programming languages make the installation of third-party code very easy. Package management tools like pip (for Python), Gems (for Ruby) or npm (for Javascript) make importing code simple.](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/third-party-code) 

Toxic Dependencies 

[However, even though development teams rarely perform code reviews on third-party dependencies, such code may contain vulnerabilities - or worse, may contain code written with malicious intent!](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/libraries-as-a-target) 

[Vulnerabilities in popular software packages are an extremely attractive target for hackers simply because many, many sites or organizations may be affected. Let's look at the some recent examples.](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/log4j) 

[Log4J is a Java-based, massively popular logging utility, used by over 35,000 Java packages. Nearly 5% of all packages in the Java ecosystem use the library to write logs!](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/the-log4j-vulnerability) 

Log4J 

import org.apache.logging.log4j.LogManager; import org.apache.logging.log4j.Logger;  public class Log4jExample {      // Define a logger using Log4j private static final Logger logger = LogManager.getLogger(Log4jExample.class);  public static void main(String[] args) {         // Log messages at different levels         logger.trace("This is a TRACE message");         logger.debug("This is a DEBUG message");         logger.info("This is an INFO message");         logger.warn("This is a WARN message");         logger.error("This is an ERROR message");         logger.fatal("This is a FATAL message");     } } 

[At the end of 2021 a vulnerability was discovered in Log4J that permitted attackers to perform remote code execution by exploiting insecure JNDI lookups in the library. Hundreds of millions of software applications had to patch the "Log4Shell" exploit - including Minecraft!](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/ruby-on-rails) 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

[In the Ruby community, Ruby on Rails is the most common web-stack - and the ubiquity of Rails means it is a great target for hackers.](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/mass-assignment) 

attribute_assignment.rb 

def _assign_attributes(attributes)  multi_parameter_attributes = nested_parameter_attributes = nil   attributes.each do |k, v|    key = k.to_s     if key.include?("(")      (multi_parameter_attributes ||= {})[key] = v    elsif v.is_a?(Hash)      (nested_parameter_attributes ||= {})[key] = v    else      _assign_attribute(key, v)    end  end   assign_nested_parameter_attributes(nested_parameter_attributes) if nested_parameter_attributes  assign_multiparameter_attributes(multi_parameter_attributes) if multi_parameter_attributes end 

[Rails intelligently maps query parameters to model state, which saves a lot of boilerplate code. However, version 3.0 of the Rails framework was vulnerable to arbitrary mass assignment - meaning carefully crafted HTTP requests could overwrite protected state in the data-model.](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/github) 

![](data:image/png;base64,)  

[One hacker (thankfully a "whitehat") used the vulnerability to gain administrative access to Github!](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/xcode) 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

[Even the development tools we use day-to-day aren't immune. In 2015, security researchers discovered maliciously modified version of XCode - the most popular development tool for OSX - being used by several hundred Chinese developers.](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/xcodeghost) 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

["XCodeGhost", as it became known, was designed to steal system information, and to inject a malicious payload into any apps built and deployed using XCode. Since XCode is commonly used to develop iPhone apps, this meant infected apps made into the iTunes store!](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/supply-chain-attacks) 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

[In 2020, SolarWinds, the maker of a network management tool called Orion, was the victim of a "supply-chain attack". By taking over the build system, hackers were able to inject a backdoor that was injected into a security update. This update was download by more than 18,000 users, including departments of the US government and Fortune 500 companies.](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/heartbleed) 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

[In 2014, the "Heartbleed" vulnerability was discovered in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library. A missing bounds-check in the code caused 1% of the world's websites to be vulnerable to an exploit that allowed an attacker to read large chunks of memory on the server.](https://www.hacksplaining.com/lessons/toxic-dependencies/try-it)
